--- !u!114 &1008417464
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1008417461}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: dbefc55dcf6fd4242a5ebcd31ba89c98, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  finalQuestions:
  - questionInfo: Which factor primarily determines the differential biological activity
      of  enantiomers?
    questionChoices:
    - The difference in how each enantiomer rotates plane-polarized light.
    - The distinct spatial arrangement around the chirality center.
    - The difference in solubility between enantiomers in aqueous and non aqueous
      environments.
    - The unique ability of each enantiomer to form covalent bonds with  proteins.
    correctChoice: The distinct spatial arrangement around the chirality center.
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: "An esophageal biopsy sample form a 47-year-old male with chronic 
      heartburn reveals intestinal metaplasia, which of the following abnormal cell 
      types is likely present in this patient\u2019s esophagus."
    questionChoices:
    - simple cuboidal epithelium
    - Pseudo stratified related kilometer epithelium
    - Poly morph nuclear leukocytes
    - Goblet cells
    correctChoice: Goblet cells
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: "A 28-year old woman comes to the ER with acute onset of abdominal
      pain ,  nausea and confusion . She has no significant past medical history
      and does  not use tobacco or alcohol as they have made her feel sick in the
      past .  serum lipase and liver function tests are within normal limits . CT
      scan of the  abdomen shows no abnormalities . A sample of her urine is reddish
      in color  and darkens on standing for 24 hours. Intravenous dextrose is administered 
      and her symptoms improve significantly . Dextrose infusion most likely  improved
      this patient\u2019s condition by affecting which of the following  pathways
      ?"
    questionChoices:
    - Gluconeogenesis
    - Purine degradation
    - Porphyrin synthesis
    - Fatty acid synthesis
    correctChoice: Porphyrin synthesis
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: "A 57-year-old woman is brought to the emergency department after
      an episode  of hematemesis. Medical history is notable for hypertension, peripheral
      vascular  disease, atrial fibrillation, and acute cystitis diagnosed three
      days ago. The  patient takes furosemide, rivaroxaban, and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole. 
      Temperature is 37.7\xB0C, pulse is 76bpm, and blood pressure is 138/75 mmHg. 
      Dried blood is noticed around the patient\u2019s mouth. Mild epigastric tenderness
      is  elicited with palpation of the abdomen. Which of the following best explains
      the  cause of this patient\u2019s symptoms?"
    questionChoices:
    - 'Perforation of distended esophageal vessel '
    - Inhibition of cytochrome P450 enzyme
    - Loss of clotting factors in urine
    - Formation of autoantibodies against platelet factor
    correctChoice: Inhibition of cytochrome P450 enzyme
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: A 15-year old girl is evaluated due to persistent fever, fatigue
      , and sore  throat . Physical examination reveals splenomegaly and symmetric 
      posterior cervical lymphadenopathy . Peripheral blood smear results  are shown
      in the image below .The atypical cells seen here are most likely an activated
      form of which of the  following ?
    questionChoices:
    - CD4+ Helper lymphocytes
    - CD8+ Cytotoxic lymphocytes
    - CD14+ Monocytes
    - CD21+ Lymphocytes
    correctChoice: CD8+ Cytotoxic lymphocytes
    questionImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 0e6035b335750464584ceb78967a23fe, type: 3}
  - questionInfo: When stained with Congo red, which of the following will exhibit
      an  apple green color?
    questionChoices:
    - Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma
    - Follicular thyroid carcinoma
    - Medullary thyroid carcinoma
    - Papillary thyroid carcinoma
    correctChoice: Medullary thyroid carcinoma
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: Why does the addition of H2 to C2H4 (ethylene) occur in a cis orientation?
    questionChoices:
    - The addition of H2 to C2H4 occurs through a syn addition  mechanism on a metal
      catalyst, resulting in both hydrogen atoms  adding to the same side of the
      double bond.
    - 'The addition of H2 to C2H4 is driven by the anti addition  mechanism, which
      places hydrogen atoms on opposite sides of  the double bond. '
    - 'The cis orientation is a result of hydrogen atoms preferring to add  to the
      less substituted carbon atoms. '
    - 'The reaction intermediates favor the trans orientation, but steric  hindrance
      forces the addition to be in the cis orientation. '
    correctChoice: The addition of H2 to C2H4 occurs through a syn addition  mechanism
      on a metal catalyst, resulting in both hydrogen atoms  adding to the same side
      of the double bond.
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: Which laboratory finding is most characteristic of post-streptococcal 
      glomerulonephritis?
    questionChoices:
    - elevated serum IGA levels
    - Normal complement levels (C3 and C4)
    - Elevated anti-strep to license oh (ASO) titer
    - Hematuria within 1-2 days of an upper respiratory infection
    correctChoice: Elevated anti-strep to license oh (ASO) titer
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: During a neurology lecture, students learn that the thalamus is
      the central  relay station for all ascending sensory information, except for
      olfaction. Which  of the following thalamic nuclei relays auditory information?
    questionChoices:
    - Medial geniculate nucleus
    - Lateral geniculate nucleus
    - Ventral posterolateral nucleus
    - Ventral posteromedial nucleus
    correctChoice: Medial geniculate nucleus
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: A B-blocker was prescribed for hypertension in a patient with asthma.
      After a  week of treatment, the asthma attacks got worse, and the patient was
      asked  to stop taking the B-blocker. Which B-blocker would you suggest as an 
      alternative that is less likely to worsen the asthma?
    questionChoices:
    - Propranolol
    - Metoprolol
    - Labetalol
    - Carvedilol
    correctChoice: Metoprolol
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: If an excessive amount of alkali is ingested, what physiological 
      compensation is most likely to occur to moderate the resulting changes in 
      blood pH?
    questionChoices:
    - Respiratory compensation through an increase in CO2 retention.
    - Respiratory compensation through an increase in H2 retention.
    - Metabolic compensation through an increase in H+ reabsorption.
    - Metabolic compensation through a decrease in HCO3-reabsorption.
    correctChoice: Respiratory compensation through an increase in CO2 retention.
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: A clinician is concerned that an Rh-negative mother may be pregnant 
      with an Rh-positive fetus. The potential pathology that the clinician is  concerned
      about is classified as which of the following immune  reactions?
    questionChoices:
    - Graft-versus-host disease
    - Type I hypersensitivity
    - Type II hypersensitivity
    - 'Type III hypersensitivity '
    correctChoice: Type II hypersensitivity
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: A 32-year-old female presents for evaluation of fatigue. She is
      a runner and  typically runs approximately 25 miles per week. For the past
      week, she has been  unable to complete a one-mile run. She denies fever, cough
      or chest pain. Pulse is  60/min and blood pressure is 120/80 mmHg. Lungs are
      clear and jugular venous  pressure is normal. A 3/6 holosystolic murmur is
      heard at the cardiac apex. ECG  shows normal sinus rhythm with a normal axis
      and intervals. Prior clinic notes  document a systolic click with no murmur.
      Which of the following is expected in this  patient at rest for cardiac output
      and pulse pressure compared to a normal patient  of similar size?
    questionChoices:
    - Both are decreased
    - Both are increased
    - "Cardiac output is increased while there\u2019s no change in pulse pressure"
    - Cardiac output is increased while pulse pressure is decreased
    correctChoice: "Cardiac output is increased while there\u2019s no change in pulse
      pressure"
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  - questionInfo: John, a 35-year-old avid tennis player, participates in a weekend
      tennis  tournament. During the final match, John lunges forward to reach a
      low,  fast-moving ball. As he extends his arm to hit the ball with full force,
      he  feels a sharp pain in his shoulder and chest. Post-match, John notices 
      persistent pain around his shoulder blade (scapula) and difficulty lifting
      his  arm above his head. His shoulder blade appears to protrude abnormally 
      when he pushes against a wall. What is the nerve that was damaged and  the
      muscle it supplies?
    questionChoices:
    - Long thoracic nerve, supraspinatous
    - Suprascapular nerve, serratus anterior
    - Long thoracic nerve, serratus anterior
    - Suprascapular nerve, supraspinatous
    correctChoice: Long thoracic nerve, serratus anterior
    questionImage: {fileID: 0}
  quizUIobj: {fileID: 609381636}
  timerObj: {fileID: 1981497918}
